  "prompt": "Is it correct to use the phrase \"revert back\" in a sentence? I hear it all the time and on occasion even on BBC!",
  "response": "The phrase \"revert back\" is generally considered redundant and grammatically incorrect by language experts. \n\n\"Revert\" already means \"to go back\" or \"to return to a previous state,\" so adding \"back\" is unnecessary. The correct usage would simply be \"revert.\"\n\nFor example:\n\u2713 Incorrect: \"I will revert back to you soon.\"\n\u2713 Correct: \"I will revert to you soon.\"\n\nAnother example:\n\u2713 Incorrect: \"The system will revert back to its default settings.\"\n\u2713 Correct: \"The system will revert to its default settings.\"\n\nDespite its frequent use (even by professional communicators like those at the BBC), it is considered a grammatical error by most style guides and language professionals. The redundancy comes from the fact that \"revert\" inherently implies going back.\n\nThat said, language is dynamic, and widespread usage can eventually lead to acceptance. However, in formal writing or professional communication, it's best to avoid \"revert back.\"",
